## Library Recommendations

| Library | Purpose | Install |
|---------|---------|---------|
| `p-limit` | Cap concurrent Playwright operations | `npm i p-limit` |
| `p-queue` | Priority queue for replies (urgent vs deferred) | `npm i p-queue` |
| `better-queue` | Persistent file-based reply queue (survives restarts) | `npm i better-queue` |
| `pino` | Fast structured logging per worker | `npm i pino` |
| `pino-pretty` | Human-readable log formatting in dev | `npm i -D pino-pretty` |
| `node-cron` | Better cron-style scheduling for heartbeat, cleanup | `npm i node-cron` |
| `electron-log` | Electron-aware log file rotation | `npm i electron-log` |

*No Redis, PostgreSQL, or paid services needed for the 20-30 account target.*

---

## Hardware Requirements for Scale Targets

| Accounts | RAM Needed | CPU Cores | Notes |
|----------|-----------|-----------|-------|
| 10 | 2 GB | 2 | Works on any modern laptop |
| 20–30 | 4–6 GB | 4 | i5/Ryzen 5 + 8GB RAM machine |
| 50–100 | 10–15 GB | 8 | Dedicated PC or small VPS |
| 1000 | Multi-machine cluster | Many | Need worker pool + Redis architecture |

---

## Implementation Order

```
Phase 1: Browser optimization (lean flags)         → 3 hours  → -60% RAM
Phase 2: Staggered polling + p-limit               → 4 hours  → stable CPU
Phase 5: Active heartbeat (30-day sessions)        → 3 hours  → no re-logins
Phase 4: Persistent reply queue (better-queue)     → 5 hours  → no lost replies
Phase 7: Account state machine                     → 4 hours  → better visibility
Phase 3: Process isolation (child_process workers) → 1-2 days → crash resilience
```

> [!NOTE]
> The 30-day reply window is **already implemented** — reply contexts are in SQLite with 30-day TTL. You can already reply to a 30-day-old Telegram notification as long as the app hasn't been restarted more than 30 days ago.
